Age: 54
Gender: Male
Occupation: Construction worker
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, obesity, and occasional smoking

Case Report:

John Smith, a 54-year-old Caucasian construction worker, presented to the emergency department with a two-day history of fever, cough, and shortness of breath. He reported working on a construction site with several other workers who had also developed similar symptoms. He denied any recent travel history or close contact with known COVID-19 positive individuals.

On examination, he was found to have a temperature of 38.7°C, heart rate of 110 beats per minute, respiratory rate of 24 breaths per minute, and oxygen saturation of 91% on room air. Lung examination revealed bilateral crackles and reduced breath sounds in the lower lung fields. A chest X-ray showed bilateral patchy infiltrates consistent with viral pneumonia.

A nasopharyngeal swab was collected and sent for real-time reverse transcriptase polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) testing for COVID-19. The test came back positive, confirming the diagnosis of COVID-19.

Age: 45
Gender: Male
Occupation: Construction worker
Ethnicity: Hispanic
Past Medical History: Hypertension, obesity

Case Report:

John Doe is a 45-year-old Hispanic male who presented to the emergency department with fever, cough, and shortness of breath. He reported having symptoms for the past 5 days and had not sought medical attention until his symptoms worsened. He denied any recent travel or known exposure to COVID-19.

On physical examination, John was found to have a temperature of 101°F, respiratory rate of 24 breaths/minute, and oxygen saturation of 92% on room air. Lung auscultation revealed bilateral crackles. Laboratory testing showed leukopenia, lymphopenia, and elevated C-reactive protein (CRP) levels. A chest X-ray showed bilateral infiltrates consistent with COVID-19.

John was admitted to the hospital and started on supplemental oxygen, remdesivir, and dexamethasone. He required high-flow nasal cannula and eventually intubation due to worsening respiratory distress. He was transferred to the ICU for further management.

Name: John Doe
Age: 45
Gender: Male
Occupation: Software Engineer
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: None reported

Introduction:
John Doe is a 45-year-old male who presented to the emergency room with symptoms suggestive of COVID-19. He reported having a fever, cough, shortness of breath, and body aches for the past five days. He denied any recent travel or close contact with someone who has tested positive for COVID-19.

Clinical Findings:
Upon physical examination, John's vital signs were as follows: temperature 101.2°F, heart rate 100 beats per minute, respiratory rate 22 breaths per minute, and oxygen saturation 93% on room air. Lung auscultation revealed diffuse crackles and wheezes bilaterally. Laboratory testing revealed elevated inflammatory markers and a positive nasopharyngeal swab for SARS-CoV-2.

Management and Outcome:
John was admitted to the hospital and started on supplemental oxygen via a nasal cannula. He was also initiated on remdesivir and dexamethasone per hospital protocol for COVID-19. His respiratory status gradually improved over the next few days, and he was able to be weaned off oxygen support

Name: John Doe
Age: 45
Gender: Male
Occupation: Construction worker
Ethnicity: African American
Past Medical History: Hypertension, obesity

Case Report:

John Doe, a 45-year-old African American construction worker, presented to the emergency department with a fever, cough, and shortness of breath. He had been feeling unwell for the past week and his symptoms progressively worsened. He reported no recent travel or known contact with anyone with COVID-19.

On examination, his temperature was 101.5°F, heart rate was 110 beats per minute, respiratory rate was 24 breaths per minute, and oxygen saturation was 92% on room air. Lung auscultation revealed bilateral crackles.

A chest X-ray showed bilateral ground-glass opacities. A nasopharyngeal swab was taken for SARS-CoV-2 testing, which came back positive.
